1. Cloud Computing (Fundamentals)

Cloud computing refers to the on-demand delivery of IT resources over the internet, eliminating the need to buy, own, and maintain physical data centers and servers.

Instead of managing infrastructure, you can access services such as:

    Compute power (e.g., virtual servers)
    Storage (e.g., Amazon S3)
    Databases (e.g., Amazon RDS, DynamoDB)
    Networking (e.g., Amazon VPC)
    AI/ML, analytics, and security services

Key advantage: You pay only for what you use, when you use it‚Äîenabling cost savings, faster innovation, and the flexibility to scale as your needs evolve.

2. AWS Cloud

Amazon Web Services (AWS) is the world‚Äôs most comprehensive and widely adopted cloud platform.
It provides a pay-as-you-go model where you can provision resources instantly and globally through a web interface, SDK, or APIs.
AWS cloud services support everything from startups to enterprise-level applications, offering tools to build, deploy, and manage applications securely and reliably at scale.

Real-World Use Case:
A startup wants to launch a mobile app. Instead of buying physical servers, they use AWS services like:
    Amazon EC2 for virtual servers
    Amazon S3 to store images and videos
    Amazon RDS for their backend database
    They save costs and scale instantly based on traffic.

